{"docs":[{"_index":"v2_api_v2","_type":"item","_id":"b002e5ee-3096-3f51-9925-32b157740c98","_version":2,"found":true,"_source":{"id":"http://www.ft.com/thing/b002e5ee-3096-3f51-9925-32b157740c98","bodyXML":"<body><p>Back to wait-and-see mode.</p>\n<p>The Bank of Korea held its key interest rate steady, a month after cutting the rate to a record-low 1.75 per cent.</p>\n<p>The case for loose monetary easing is clear: growth is slowing, Korean inflation is running at a <a href=\"http://on.ft.com/1yxrUCE\">16-year low</a> and unemployment is running at <a href=\"http://on.ft.com/1EubLCw\">a 12-month high.</a> </p>\n<p>But with household debts on the rise, Governor Lee Ju-Yeol could be reluctant to cut rates even further. </p>\n<p>The decision to keep policy steady syncs with decisions this week from Australia, Japan and India.</p>\n<p>The BoK was largely expected to hold fire. Those expecting a cut this quarter include BNP Paribas, DBS, Deutsche Bank, and Societe Generale. </p></body>","title":"Bank of Korea keeps rates at 1.75%","publishedDate":"2015-04-09T01:05:09.000Z","requestUrl":"http://mapi.ft.com/enrichedcontent/b002e5ee-3096-3f51-9925-32b157740c98","brands":["http://api.ft.com/things/5c7592a8-1f0c-11e4-b0cb-b2227cce2b54","http://api.ft.com/things/dbb0bdae-1f0c-11e4-b0cb-b2227cce2b54"],"annotations":[{"predicate":"http://www.ft.com/ontology/annotation/mentions","uri":"http://api.ft.com/things/b390da94-0f62-38b2-9e6d-1b08662f4cb8","apiUrl":"http://mapi.ft.com/organisations/b390da94-0f62-38b2-9e6d-1b08662f4cb8","label":"Deutsche Bank AG","type":"ORGANISATION"},{"predicate":"http://www.ft.com/ontology/annotation/mentions","uri":"http://api.ft.com/things/62124d69-2a34-33d9-8341-ad21625a183f","apiUrl":"http://mapi.ft.com/organisations/62124d69-2a34-33d9-8341-ad21625a183f","label":"The Bank of Korea","type":"ORGANISATION"},{"predicate":"http://www.ft.com/ontology/classification/isClassifiedBy","uri":"http://api.ft.com/things/dbb0bdae-1f0c-11e4-b0cb-b2227cce2b54","apiU